import{a as e}from"./chunk-5DCJDTUX.js";import"./chunk-IFGU66OU.js";var a={meta:e,sections:[{id:"overview",title:"Overview",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Spotify is a **music + podcast streaming** service: **600M+ users**, a catalog of **100M+ tracks**, and **billions of streams/day**. Unlike video, each item is **small** (a few MB) but the **catalog is enormous** and **playback must start almost instantly**. The defining challenges are **low-latency audio delivery** (with gapless prefetch), **playlists & libraries** at scale, **offline downloads**, and a world-class **discovery/recommendation** engine."},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"The big idea",body:"Separate three concerns: a **catalog + search** layer over a massive but slowly-changing library; a **delivery** layer that streams small encrypted audio segments from a CDN with aggressive **prefetching** for instant, gapless playback; and a **personalization** layer (recommendations, Discover Weekly, autoplay/radio) powered by collaborative filtering + audio analysis over a firehose of play events."},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"How this differs from Netflix / YouTube",body:"Files are tiny vs video, so **storage and bandwidth are modest** \u2014 the hard parts shift to **catalog scale**, **instant start + gapless transitions**, **playlist/library writes**, **licensing/royalties accounting**, and **recommendations** as the core product, not an add-on."},{type:"image",src:"assets/diagrams/spotify-architecture.svg",alt:"Spotify architecture: listener connects through the gateway to streaming, catalog/search, and playlist services; audio segments are served from a CDN; recommendations power discovery; play events flow to Kafka for analytics and ML.",caption:"Three concerns: catalog/search, low-latency CDN audio delivery, and the personalization engine \u2014 tied together by a play-event stream."}]},{id:"functional-requirements",title:"Functional Requirements",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"We scope the interview to the music-streaming + discovery core."},{type:"bestPractices",title:"In scope",practices:["**Search & browse** the catalog (tracks, albums, artists, podcasts).","**Stream a track** with instant start and **gapless** playback.","**Playlists & library**: create, edit, follow, collaborative playlists.","**Offline downloads** for premium users.","**Personalization**: recommendations, Discover Weekly, autoplay/radio.","**Play tracking** for royalties + personalization signals."]},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Out of scope (state this explicitly)",body:"Ad serving, the full royalty/payment settlement system, artist-facing analytics (Spotify for Artists), social graph internals, and the detailed ML model architecture. Naming the boundary keeps the focus on delivery, playlists, and discovery."}]},{id:"non-functional-requirements",title:"Non-Functional Requirements",blocks:[{type:"prosCons",title:"Prioritizing the qualities",pros:["Very low playback start latency (< 250ms perceived) + gapless transitions.","High availability for playback + search (target 99.95%+).","Read-heavy global scalability (streams \u226B writes).","Accurate, durable play logging for royalties.","Offline-capable clients (cached tracks + library)."],cons:["Strong global consistency NOT required for recommendations / counts.","Catalog changes can propagate with seconds-to-minutes lag.","Playlist edits can be eventually consistent across devices (with conflict handling)."]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"CAP framing",body:"Mostly **AP** for catalog, search, and recommendations. The parts that care about correctness are **play logging** (royalties must not lose plays) and **playlist edits** (need eventual convergence without losing a user's changes \u2014 a sync/merge problem)."}]},{id:"capacity-estimation",title:"Capacity Estimation",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Assume **100M tracks**, **150M concurrent listeners** at peak, an average track of **~3.5 MB** (Ogg Vorbis ~160kbps), and **billions of streams/day**."},{type:"metrics",items:[{label:"Catalog size",value:"~100M tracks",hint:"+ podcasts"},{label:"Avg track size",value:"~3.5 MB",hint:"~160 kbps Ogg"},{label:"Catalog storage",value:"~1\u20132 PB",hint:"\xD7 quality variants"},{label:"Concurrent streams",value:"~150M",hint:"peak"},{label:"Avg bitrate",value:"~160 kbps",hint:"adaptive 96\u2013320"},{label:"Peak egress",value:"~24 Tbps",hint:"150M \xD7 160kbps"}]},{type:"markdown",value:"Note how much **smaller** this is than video. The whole catalog fits in a couple of petabytes, and peak egress is an order of magnitude below a video service:"},{type:"math",display:!0,tex:"B_{peak} = C_{streams} \\times Bitrate_{avg} = 1.5\\times10^{8} \\times 1.6\\times10^{5}\\,\\text{bps} = 2.4\\times10^{13}\\,\\text{bps} \\approx 24\\ \\text{Tbps}",caption:"Peak audio egress. Small files + modest bitrates mean the popular catalog can be cached almost entirely at the edge."},{type:"markdown",value:"Because the popular catalog is small enough to **cache aggressively at the edge** (and even on-device), the engineering effort shifts from raw bandwidth (Netflix's problem) to **catalog/search scale**, **playlist writes**, and **recommendation quality**."}]},{id:"high-level-architecture",title:"High-Level Architecture",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"The client hits the **Catalog/Search** service to find music and the **Streaming Service** to play it \u2014 which returns a short-lived, signed segment URL plus a license, and the client streams encrypted audio from the **CDN**. **Playlist/Library** services manage user collections. Every play emits an event to **Kafka**, feeding analytics, royalties, and the **Recommendation** engine."},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Catalog/search, CDN audio delivery, playlists, and the personalization loop.",definition:`flowchart TD
  Client["Client (app / web)"] --> GW["API Gateway"]
  GW --> Cat["Catalog / Search"]
  Cat --> CatDB[("Catalog DB: Cassandra")]
  Cat --> ES[("Search index: ES")]
  GW --> Stream["Streaming Service"]
  Stream --> Lic["License / DRM"]
  Stream --> CDN["Audio CDN (segments)"]
  Client -->|encrypted audio| CDN
  GW --> PL["Playlist / Library"]
  PL --> PLDB[("Playlists: Cassandra/SQL")]
  Client -->|play events| K[("Kafka: play.events")]
  K --> Royalty["Royalty / Analytics"]
  K --> Reco["Recommendation Engine"]
  Reco --> RecoCache[("Per-user reco cache")]
  RecoCache --> GW`},{type:"architectureCard",title:"Streaming Service",description:"Authorizes playback, issues a short-lived signed URL + decryption license, and helps the client prefetch upcoming segments/tracks for gapless playback. Treats audio as immutable, edge-cacheable segments.",icon:"play",tags:["delivery","prefetch","drm"]},{type:"architectureCard",title:"Catalog / Search",description:"Serves the huge, slowly-changing library: track/album/artist metadata in a wide-column store, full-text + fuzzy search in Elasticsearch. Heavily cached; updated as labels deliver new content.",icon:"search",tags:["catalog","search","cacheable"]},{type:"architectureCard",title:"Recommendation Engine",description:"Generates personalized playlists (Discover Weekly, Daily Mixes, radio) from collaborative filtering over play events, audio content analysis, and NLP over playlists/web. Precomputed offline, served from a per-user cache.",icon:"sparkles",tags:["ml","collaborative-filtering","offline"]}]},{id:"audio-delivery",title:"Audio Delivery & Gapless Playback",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"The product-defining metric is **time-to-play**. Spotify famously targets sub-quarter-second perceived start. It achieves this with small encrypted segments served from a CDN, **adaptive bitrate** (96/160/320 kbps), and **predictive prefetching**: while one track plays, the next is already being fetched, enabling **gapless** transitions."},{type:"bestPractices",title:"Low-latency audio best practices",practices:["**Start at a safe bitrate** and adapt up, so the first audio plays immediately.","**Prefetch the next track** (and the rest of the current one) during playback.","**On-device cache** recently/likely-played tracks to make replays instant and save bandwidth.","**Edge-cache the popular catalog** \u2014 a small hot set serves most streams.","**Gapless**: decode-ahead and crossfade boundaries so playlists flow seamlessly."]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Predictive prefetch is the trick",body:"In a playlist or album, the *next* track is highly predictable. Fetching it before the current one ends turns every transition into an instant, gapless start \u2014 the single biggest perceived-performance win in music streaming."},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"P2P history",body:"Early Spotify combined a CDN with a **peer-to-peer** network (clients shared cached tracks) to cut server bandwidth and latency. They later retired P2P as CDN economics improved \u2014 a good example of an architecture evolving with cost curves."}]},{id:"api-design",title:"API Design",blocks:[{type:"apiTable",title:"Core endpoints",endpoints:[{method:"GET",path:"/v1/search?q=&type=",description:"Search tracks/albums/artists",auth:!1},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/tracks/{id}",description:"Track metadata",auth:!1},{method:"POST",path:"/v1/tracks/{id}/play",description:"Authorize playback \u2192 signed URL + license",auth:!0},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/me/playlists",description:"User playlists / library",auth:!0},{method:"POST",path:"/v1/playlists",description:"Create a playlist",auth:!0},{method:"PUT",path:"/v1/playlists/{id}/tracks",description:"Reorder / add / remove (sync-aware)",auth:!0},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/me/discover-weekly",description:"Personalized weekly mix",auth:!0},{method:"POST",path:"/v1/me/plays",description:"Report a completed play (royalty + signal)",auth:!0}]},{type:"markdown",value:"A play authorization returns a **short-lived signed URL** plus a license, and a list of upcoming segments to prefetch. Play reporting is durable (royalties) but tolerant of retries via an idempotency key."},{type:"code",language:"json",filename:"play-response.json",highlightLines:[3,4,9],code:`{
  "track": { "id": "t_5x9", "title": "Nightcall", "durationMs": 257000 },
  "audio": {
    "url": "https://cdn.spot.com/a/5x9?exp=...&sig=...",   // short-lived signed
    "format": "ogg", "bitrates": [96000, 160000, 320000]
  },
  "license": "base64-drm-license...",
  "prefetch": [
    { "trackId": "t_6a1", "url": "https://cdn.spot.com/a/6a1?..." }   // next track
  ]
}`}]},{id:"database-design",title:"Database Design",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Polyglot persistence: the catalog in a wide-column store + search index, playlists/library in a store tuned for many small per-user writes, audio in blob+CDN, and play logs streamed for royalties + ML."},{type:"code",language:"sql",filename:"catalog.cql",highlightLines:[3,11],code:`-- Tracks: read-heavy, rarely changing, looked up by id.
CREATE TABLE tracks (
  track_id   text PRIMARY KEY,
  title      text,
  artist_id  text,
  album_id   text,
  duration_ms int,
  audio_keys map<int, text>,   -- bitrate -> blob key
  available_markets set<text>  -- licensing per country
);
-- Playlist items: partition by playlist, ordered position for sequence.
CREATE TABLE playlist_items (
  playlist_id uuid,
  position    bigint,          -- gap-based ordering for cheap reorders
  track_id    text,
  added_by    bigint,
  PRIMARY KEY ((playlist_id), position)
) WITH CLUSTERING ORDER BY (position ASC);`},{type:"table",caption:"Data store chosen per workload.",headers:["Data","Store","Why"],rows:[["Audio files","Blob store + CDN","Immutable, edge-cacheable, small"],["Catalog metadata","Cassandra + cache","Read-heavy, slowly changing"],["Search index","Elasticsearch","Full-text + fuzzy + typeahead"],["Playlists / library","Cassandra (per-user)","Many small writes, partition by user/playlist"],["Play logs","Kafka \u2192 warehouse","Royalties + ML signals, append-only"],["Recommendations","Per-user cache (Redis)","Precomputed, fast serving"]]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Licensing is per-market",body:"A track is not globally available \u2014 rights differ by country. Store `available_markets` and filter at search/play time so a user only sees and streams what is licensed in their region."}]},{id:"playlists-sync",title:"Playlists & Multi-Device Sync",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Playlists are edited from many devices, sometimes offline, and **collaborative** playlists are edited by many users at once. This is a **distributed sync/merge** problem: changes must converge without losing edits. Spotify modeled playlists as an **ordered list with an operation log**, syncing operations (add/remove/move) rather than overwriting the whole list."},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"Sync operations, not snapshots",body:'Sending the full playlist on every edit causes lost updates and huge payloads. Instead, clients send **mutations** (e.g. "insert track X at position N", "move A\u2192B") against a base version; the server applies and rebroadcasts them, resolving concurrent edits \u2014 conceptually like operational transforms / CRDTs.'},{type:"code",language:"json",filename:"playlist-mutation.json",code:`{
  "playlistId": "pl_77",
  "baseVersion": 412,                 // optimistic concurrency
  "ops": [
    { "op": "add", "trackId": "t_9z2", "atPosition": 12 },
    { "op": "move", "from": 3, "to": 0 }
  ],
  "clientId": "dev_a1"                 // to ignore echo of own ops
}`},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Ordering at scale",body:"Storing positions as dense integers (0,1,2\u2026) makes a reorder rewrite many rows. Use **fractional / gap-based ordering** (e.g. positions 100, 200, 300) so inserting between two items just picks a midpoint \u2014 no mass rewrite. Periodically rebalance when gaps run out."}]},{id:"recommendations",title:"Recommendations & Discovery",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Discovery *is* the product. Spotify blends three signal sources: **collaborative filtering** (users who listen to X also listen to Y), **content-based audio analysis** (tempo, key, energy, timbre), and **NLP** over playlists, articles, and metadata. Candidates are generated and ranked **offline** (big-data jobs), then served per-user as fast lookups \u2014 powering Discover Weekly, Daily Mixes, and radio/autoplay."},{type:"bestPractices",title:"Recommendation pipeline",practices:["**Collaborative filtering** on the user\xD7track play matrix (e.g. matrix factorization).","**Audio content models** so brand-new tracks (no play history) are still recommendable.","**NLP over playlists/web** to learn cultural context and similarity.","**Generate + rank offline** (Spark/BigQuery), cache per-user candidate sets.","**Refresh on a schedule** (Discover Weekly = Mondays) and adapt radio in near-real-time."]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Solve the cold-start problem",body:"Pure collaborative filtering cannot recommend a track nobody has played yet. **Content-based audio analysis** gives every track a feature vector from the audio itself, so new releases can be matched to similar music immediately \u2014 a key reason Spotify combines both approaches."}]},{id:"communication-flow",title:"Communication Flow",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Pressing play, with prefetch and play logging:"},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Authorize \u2192 stream \u2192 prefetch next \u2192 log play.",definition:`sequenceDiagram
  participant C as Client
  participant S as Streaming Svc
  participant L as License/DRM
  participant D as CDN
  participant K as Kafka
  C->>S: POST /tracks/{id}/play
  S->>L: authorize + mint license
  L-->>S: license + signed URL
  S-->>C: url + prefetch list (next track)
  C->>D: GET audio segments (start low bitrate)
  D-->>C: encrypted audio (edge cache)
  C->>D: prefetch next track during playback
  C->>K: play completed event (>30s)
  K->>K: royalties + recommendation signal`},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:'A "stream" has rules',body:"For royalties, a play typically only counts after a threshold (e.g. 30 seconds). The client reports a completed play event, which is logged durably for accounting and fed back as a personalization signal."}]},{id:"caching-strategy",title:"Caching Strategy",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Three cache layers: the **CDN** for audio segments, **on-device** cache for recently/likely-played tracks, and server-side caches for catalog metadata, search results, and per-user recommendations. Because the popular catalog is small, hit ratios are extremely high."},{type:"code",language:"java",filename:"StreamingService.java",highlightLines:[7,8,9],code:`@Service
public class StreamingService {
  private final CatalogCache catalog;   // track metadata
  private final UrlSigner signer;       // short-lived signed CDN URLs

  public PlayResponse play(String trackId, User u) {
    Track t = catalog.get(trackId);                 // cache-aside
    requireLicensed(t, u.market());                 // per-market rights
    String url = signer.sign(t.audioKey(u.quality()), Duration.ofMinutes(5));
    return new PlayResponse(url, license(t, u), prefetchNext(u));
  }
}`},{type:"bestPractices",title:"Caching best practices applied here",practices:["**Edge-cache the hot catalog**; the long tail is fetched on demand and cached.","**On-device cache** for offline + instant replays (premium downloads).","**Cache per-user recommendations**; they change on a slow schedule.","**Short-lived signed URLs** keep audio access secure without per-request DB hits.","**TTL + jitter** to avoid synchronized cache expiry."]}]},{id:"scaling-strategy",title:"Scaling Strategy",blocks:[{type:"bestPractices",practices:["**Offload audio to the CDN + device cache** so origin handles misses, not the stream firehose.","**Read-optimize the catalog** with heavy caching; it changes slowly.","**Shard playlists/library by user** to spread the many small writes.","**Stream play events through Kafka** to decouple royalties + ML from playback.","**Precompute recommendations offline**; serve from a per-user cache.","**Autoscale stateless services**; playback is bursty around peak hours."]},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"Small files change the economics",body:"Because the catalog is only a couple of petabytes and tracks are a few MB, you can cache an enormous fraction of demand at the edge and on devices. The scaling pressure is on **metadata/search QPS, playlist writes, and recommendation compute** \u2014 not raw bandwidth."}]},{id:"consistency",title:"Consistency",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Catalog, search, and recommendations are eventually consistent. Audio is immutable. The careful parts are **playlist sync** (converge without losing edits) and **play logging** (durable for royalties). Library reads should reflect a user's own recent writes."},{type:"featureComparison",caption:"Consistency expectations by data type.",columns:["Strong","Eventual"],rows:[{feature:"Play log durability (royalties)",values:[!0,!1]},{feature:"Playlist convergence",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"Catalog / search freshness",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"Recommendations",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"Account / subscription",values:[!0,!1]}]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Read-your-own-writes for the library",body:"When a user adds a song or makes a playlist, they must see it instantly on that device. Apply edits locally (optimistic UI) and sync in the background, reconciling with the server version."}]},{id:"availability",title:"Availability",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Playback must keep working even when sub-systems degrade. The **on-device cache** means downloaded/recent tracks play even offline. If recommendations fail, fall back to recently played or editorial playlists; if search is down, serve cached/browse views. Audio comes from many edges, so an origin issue is invisible to most listeners."},{type:"callout",variant:"summary",title:"Graceful degradation",body:"A degraded experience (no fresh Discover Weekly, cached search, offline cache for playback) beats silence. Never let recommendation, search, or analytics failures stop the music."},{type:"youtube",videoId:"I7IdS-PbEgI",title:"Designing a music streaming service (illustrative embed)"}]},{id:"partitioning",title:"Partitioning",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Catalog data partitions by `track_id`/`artist_id`. Playlists partition by `playlist_id`, and a user's library by `user_id`. Play logs partition by time/user for the streaming pipeline. Audio blobs partition by hashed key prefix."},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Avoid hot partitions",body:"A viral new release or a mega-playlist (e.g. an editorial playlist with tens of millions of followers) is a hot key. Mitigate with **CDN absorption** for audio, **caching** for hot metadata, and treating massive followed-playlists as read-mostly cached objects."}]},{id:"sharding",title:"Sharding",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Wide-column stores shard by key via consistent hashing; the relational tier (users, subscriptions) shards by user id. Spotify pioneered organizing services and data ownership around autonomous **squads** and a microservices fleet, each service owning and sharding its own data."},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Service-owned, independently sharded data stores.",definition:`flowchart LR
  GW["Gateway"] --> CatSvc["Catalog Svc"] --> CatShards[("Cat shards")]
  GW --> PlSvc["Playlist Svc"] --> PlShards[("Playlist shards (by user)")]
  GW --> RecoSvc["Reco Svc"] --> RecoCache[("Per-user cache")]`}]},{id:"replication",title:"Replication",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Audio blobs replicate across zones/regions and fan out across CDN edges worldwide. Wide-column stores replicate RF=3 across AZs with quorum reads/writes. Play logs are durably replicated in the streaming pipeline before acknowledgement so royalty data is never lost."},{type:"prosCons",title:"Multi-region delivery",pros:["Survives a region outage; audio from the nearest edge.","Low global start latency.","Durable catalog + play logs across zones."],cons:["Cross-region metadata + playlist sync lag.","Operational complexity.","Replication cost (modest for audio, larger for logs)."]}]},{id:"fault-tolerance",title:"Fault Tolerance",blocks:[{type:"bestPractices",practices:["**On-device cache** keeps playback working through network/server blips.","**Durable play logging** (persist before ack) so royalties are never lost.","**Idempotent play events** keyed on `(user, track, session)` to avoid double-counting.","**Optimistic playlist edits** with server reconciliation so edits are not lost.","**Circuit breakers + fallbacks** on search, recommendations, and analytics.","**CDN absorbs origin failures** for already-cached audio."]},{type:"expandable",title:"Example: idempotent play logging",blocks:[{type:"code",language:"python",filename:"log_play.py",code:`def log_play(event):
    # Royalty-grade: exactly-once accounting from at-least-once delivery.
    key = f"play:{event.user_id}:{event.track_id}:{event.session_id}"
    if store.seen(key):           # dedupe retries / redelivered events
        return
    if event.played_ms < 30_000:  # below the royalty threshold: ignore
        return
    royalties.record(event)       # durable, append-only
    signals.emit(event)           # feed recommendations
    store.mark(key)`}]}]},{id:"trade-offs",title:"Trade-offs",blocks:[{type:"table",caption:"Key decisions and what they cost.",headers:["Decision","Gain","Cost"],rows:[["Predictive prefetch","Instant, gapless playback","Wasted bandwidth on skips"],["On-device + edge caching","Low latency, offline, cheap","Cache invalidation, storage on device"],["Sync ops (not snapshots)","Collaborative edits converge","Conflict-resolution complexity"],["Gap-based playlist ordering","Cheap reorders/inserts","Periodic rebalancing"],["Offline-precomputed reco","Fast serving, rich models","Staleness; heavy batch compute"],["Hybrid CF + content models","Solves cold start","Two model pipelines to maintain"]]}]},{id:"technology-choices",title:"Technology Choices",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"A representative slice of the stack and the role each plays:"},{type:"table",headers:["Concern","Technology"],rows:[["Audio storage","Blob store + CDN"],["Catalog metadata","Cassandra"],["Search","Elasticsearch"],["Playlists / library","Cassandra / PostgreSQL"],["Eventing / streams","Apache Kafka"],["Big-data / ML","BigQuery / Spark / TensorFlow"],["Recommendation serving","Redis (per-user cache)"],["Service platform","Microservices (squads) on GKE-like"]]},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Data-driven by design",body:"Spotify runs one of the largest data platforms in consumer tech (it open-sourced **Luigi** and **Scio** for big-data pipelines). Recommendations are not a bolt-on \u2014 the entire company is organized to turn play events into personalization."},{type:"code",language:"yaml",filename:"streaming-service.deploy.yaml",code:`service: streaming
strategy: rolling
regions: [us-east-1, eu-west-1, ap-southeast-1]
autoscaling:
  metric: rps
  target: 5000
  min: 20
  max: 600
healthCheck:
  path: /health
  unhealthyThreshold: 3`}]},{id:"interview-questions",title:"Interview Questions",blocks:[{type:"interviewQa",items:[{question:"How do you make playback start almost instantly?",answer:"Serve small encrypted audio segments from a **CDN**, start at a **safe bitrate** and adapt up, **prefetch** the next track during playback, and keep an **on-device cache** of recent/likely tracks. Because the popular catalog is small, edge + device hit ratios are very high."},{question:"How does this differ from designing Netflix or YouTube?",answer:"Files are tiny (a few MB) and the catalog fits in a couple of PB, so **bandwidth/storage are not the bottleneck**. The hard problems shift to **catalog/search scale**, **instant gapless playback**, **playlist sync (incl. collaborative)**, **per-market licensing**, and **recommendations as the core product**."},{question:"How do you handle collaborative playlist editing across devices?",answer:"Sync **operations** (add/remove/move against a base version), not full snapshots, so concurrent edits converge without lost updates \u2014 conceptually operational transforms / CRDTs. Use **gap-based ordering** so reorders/inserts do not rewrite the whole list."},{question:"How do recommendations work and how do you solve cold start?",answer:"Blend **collaborative filtering** (user\xD7track matrix) with **content-based audio analysis** and **NLP** over playlists. Content models give brand-new tracks a feature vector so they can be recommended before they have any plays \u2014 solving cold start. Candidates are computed offline and cached per user."},{question:"How do you count a stream for royalties without losing data?",answer:"Clients report a completed play (past a ~30s threshold) through **Kafka**; an **idempotent**, durable consumer records it for royalties. Keying on `(user, track, session)` makes at-least-once delivery effectively-once, so retries never double-count."},{question:"How do you respect per-country licensing?",answer:"Store `available_markets` on each track and filter at search and play-authorization time, so users only see and stream content licensed in their region. Signed, short-lived URLs enforce access at the CDN."}]}]},{id:"references",title:"References",blocks:[{type:"references",items:[{label:"Spotify Engineering Blog",url:"https://engineering.atspotify.com/",source:"Spotify"},{label:"How Spotify's Discover Weekly Works",url:"https://engineering.atspotify.com/2015/11/spotifys-discover-weekly-how-machine-learning-finds-your-new-music/",source:"Spotify"},{label:"Spotify's Event Delivery (the road to the cloud)",url:"https://engineering.atspotify.com/2016/02/spotifys-event-delivery-the-road-to-the-cloud-part-i/",source:"Spotify"},{label:"Scio: Spotify's data pipelines",url:"https://github.com/spotify/scio",source:"GitHub"},{label:"Collaborative Filtering / Matrix Factorization",url:"https://developers.google.com/machine-learning/recommendation/collaborative/matrix",source:"Google"}]}]},{id:"summary",title:"Summary",blocks:[{type:"callout",variant:"summary",title:"Key takeaways",body:`1. **Small files flip the problem**: with a couple-of-PB catalog you cache aggressively at the edge + on-device, so the focus is catalog/search, playlists, and discovery \u2014 not bandwidth.
2. **Instant + gapless playback** via adaptive bitrate and **predictive prefetch** of the next track.
3. **Sync playlists as operations, not snapshots**, with gap-based ordering for cheap reorders and collaborative convergence.
4. **Discovery is the product**: blend collaborative filtering with content-based audio models to solve cold start, computed offline and cached per user.
5. **Log plays durably and idempotently** for royalties, and respect **per-market licensing** at search + play time.`}]}]},i=a;export{i as default};
